[[File:Ronninge Show Chorus (2).jpg|thumb|350px|''[[Rönninge Show]]'', performing as reigning champions in 2014]] [[File:Love Notes Quartet.jpg|thumb|350px|''LoveNotes'' quartet performing as reigning "queens of harmony" in 2014]]The '''Sweet Adelines International Competitions''' are the annual global championships for women's [[barbershop harmony]] [[A cappella|a cappella singing]]&nbsp;– in [[quartets]] and [[choir|choruses]]&nbsp;– for members of [[Sweet Adelines International]] (SAI) and have been held annually between September and November since 1947.<ref>{{cite web|title=Competition|url=http://www.sweetadelineintl.org/index.cfm?id=7|website=Sweet Adelines International|accessdate=18 February 2015}}</ref> They are now the largest women's singing competition in the world with over 8000 participants at the 2014 convention.<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://baltimore.cbslocal.com/2014/11/07/thousands-gathering-in-baltimore-for-largest-womens-singing-competition/|title = Thousands Gathering In Baltimore For Largest Women’s Singing Competition|last = Leong|first = Tracey|date = 7 November 2014|work = CBS Baltimore|access-date = 14 February 2015}}</ref> There are two competitions for choruses (the international championships and the "Harmony Classic" for smaller choruses), and two competitions for quartets (the international championships and the "Rising Star" for young singers). Currently, the first three of these competitions are held together and form the '''Sweet Adelines International Convention'''. Over the course of competition history, the most successful chorus has been ''[[Melodeers Chorus]] ''from [[Chicago]] with seven championship titles, and the most successful quartet singer was Connie Noble who won with four separate quartets. ''Lustre Quartet'' from [[Baltimore]] holds the record for highest quartet score, and ''[[Rönninge Show Chorus]]'' from [[Stockholm]] for highest ever chorus score.<ref>{{cite conference |url= http://pure.ltu.se/portal/en/publications/assessment-of-musical-quality(0daaa4dc-f4bb-4979-9d20-378354dae2ab).html|title= Assessment of musical quality: a case study of achieving a World Champion title in chorus singing|first1= Susanna|last1= Leijonhufvud|last2= Nyberg |first2 = Johan|author-link= |date= 25 April 2014 |conference= Nordic Network for Research in Music Education}}</ref> ==History== The first convention was held in Tulsa, Oklahoma in 1947 for quartets&nbsp;– two years after the foundation of the first ''Sweet Adelines Inc.'' chapter in the city.<ref>{{cite news|title=Women Vocalists To Form 'Sweet Adelines' Group|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/2310471/sweet_adelines_first_convention/|newspaper=[[The Miami Daily News-Record]]|date=3 October 1947|page=1|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate =27 April 2015}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Women Will Form Sweet Adelines Inc.|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/2310436/sweet_adelines_first_convention/|newspaper=[[Joplin Globe]]|date=3 October 1947|page=12|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = 27 April 2015}} {{Open access}}</ref> The competition was expanded to include choruses in 1973 and in 2000 the Harmony Classic competition for small and medium-sized choruses was introduced. Originally, Harmony Classic was held independently but since 2009 all three are now hosted together and run over the course of the convention week. A fourth event, the "Rising Star" competition, was introduced in 1999 for quartets whose members are under-25 years old. It was also held as part of convention from 2009 until 2012 but due to scheduling and cost constraints is now held independently again. Many non-competitive performances are also held during convention week, including by the previous year's chorus and quartet champions.
The convention is usually held in a city in the [[continental United States]] but has thrice been held internationally (England 1977, Canada 1962, 2007) and four times in Hawaii (1969, 1987, 2008, 2013). A "spectacular fifty-year anniversary celebration" was held in New Orleans during the 1995 convention<ref>{{Cite book|title = The Barbershop Singer: Inside the Social World of a Musical Hobby|last = Stebbins|first = Robert|publisher = University of Toronto Press|year = 1996|isbn = 9780802078292|location = |pages = 29}}</ref>{{sfn|50 and Forward|1995}} and the competition was to be held there a decade later in 2005, but was moved due to [[Hurricane Katrina]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.acappellanews.com/archive/000900.html|title = Sweet Adelines Convention Cancelled|date = 31 August 2005|accessdate = 26 April 2015|website = A Cappella News|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> From 2015 to 2017, the city of Las Vegas hosted the convention&nbsp;– the first time that the event has stayed in the same location for more than one year. The 2020 "75th Diamond Anniversary" convention is expected to be the first use of the newly renovated [[Kentucky International Convention Center]] in Louisville, Kentucky<ref>{{cite web|title=Future Convention Dates|url=http://www.sweetadelineintl.org/index.cfm?id=334|website=Sweet Adelines International|accessdate=13 February 2015}}</ref>&nbsp;– expecting to draw 10,000 attendees.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.courier-journal.com/story/money/2015/02/13/timeline-set-huge-convention-center-project/23346077/|title = Timeline set for huge convention center project|date = 13 February 2015|accessdate = 14 February 2015|website = [[The Courier-Journal]]|publisher = |last = Shafer|first = Sheldon}}</ref>
